%N A394632 Least prime q such that q^2 - n! is again the square of a prime, or 0 if no such prime exists.
%C A394632 Upon the observation that 7^2 - 5^2 = 49 - 25 = 24 = 4!, it is natural to ask whether there are primes p, q such that q^2 - p^2 = n! for all n >= 4.
%C A394632 If d1 * d2 = n! = q^2 - p^2 = (q + p) * (q - p) then we can set d1 = (q - p) and d2 = (q + p). Solving for p and q in terms of d1 and d2 gives p = abs((d1 - d2) / 2) and q = (d1 + d2)/2. As p and q are prime we must have gcd(d1, d2) = 2. - _David A. Corneth_, Apr 04 2026
%H A394632 David A. Corneth, <a href="/A394632/a394632.gp.txt">PARI program</a>
%F A394632 a(n) = sqrt(A394631(n)^2 + A000142(n)^2) = A000040(A394633(n)).
%e A394632 See A394631.
%o A394632 (PARI) apply( {A394632(n,f=n!)=n>3&&forprime(p=3,oo,issquare(p^2+f,&q)&& isprime(q)&& return(q))}, [0..16]) /* For illustration, slow for n > 20. Better use: */
%o A394632 {A394632(n)=sqrtint(A394631(n)^2+n!)}  /* with more efficient code given there */
%o A394632 (PARI) \\ See Corneth link
%o A394632 (PARI) a(n)=if(n<4,return(0));my(N=n!,L=List());fordiv(vecprod(primes([3,n])),d,my(U=2*gcd(d^n,N));my(p=(N/U+U)/2,q=abs(N/U-U)/2); if(ispseudoprime(q)&&ispseudoprime(p), listput(L, [p, q]))); vecsort(Vec(L))[1][1]; \\ _Daniel Suteu_, Apr 10 2026
%Y A394632 Cf. A001248 (squares of primes), A000142 (factorial).
%Y A394632 Cf. A394631 (primes p = sqrt(a(n)^2 - n!)), A394633 (primepi(a(n))), A394629 (total number of primes {p, q} s.t. q^2 - p^2 = n!).
%K A394632 nonn
%O A394632 0,5
